<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911114-0090</DOCNO><DOCID>911114-0090.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Columbia Pictures Buys   `October Surprise' Rights</HL><DATE>11/14/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><CO>   SNE</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)HOME ELECTRONICS, FURNISHINGS, APPLIANCES (HMF)RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY (REC)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc. andits former co-chairman, Jon Peters, acquired the film rightson a controversial new book by Gary Sick about the 1980presidential election and the Iranian hostage release.   Terms of the purchase weren't disclosed, but a personclose to the deal said it was worth about $500,000. Thepicture is expected to begin shooting in 1992; it's scheduledfor release in 1993.</LP><TEXT>   The deal marks the first major acquisition for PetersEntertainment Co., which will produce the film. Mr. Peters'snew entertainment venture is exclusively tied to Columbia, aunit of Japan's Sony Corp.   The book, &quot;October Surprise: America's Hostages in Iranand the Election of Ronald Reagan,&quot; puts forth the theorythat the Reagan-Bush campaign made a secret deal with theIranian government to delay the release of the U.S. hostagesuntil after the November 1980 election. Its allegations havestirred debate in Congress, and was criticized in two recentcover stories in Newsweek and the New Republic magazines. Mr.Sick was a former National Security Council specialist underPresidents Ford and Carter.</TEXT></DOC>